        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Sacco and Vanzetti case exemplified the anti-immigrant and anti-radical prejudices of 1920s America. Their trial for murder was marked by ethnic and political bias against them as Italian immigrants and anarchists. Despite international protests and questionable evidence, their conviction and execution demonstrated the era's strong prejudices against both immigrants and radical political beliefs.</explanation>
